{{Infobox Military Structure |name= Royal Air Force Station Needs Oar Point |ensign=[[File:Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg|90px]] |partof= |location= [[Hampshire]], [[England]] |latd=50|latm=46|lats=23|latNS=N |longd=1|longm=25|longs=53|longEW=W |coord_region = GB-HAM |coord_display = inline,title |pushpin_map = Hampshire |pushpin_label_position = top |image= Needs Oar Point airfield.jpg |caption= The location of the airfield in 2014 |type= Airfield |code= |built= |builder= |materials= |height= |used= 1943-1945 |demolished= |condition=Closed |commanders= |occupants=[[No. 146 Wing RAF]] |battles=Second World War |events= }} '''Royal Air Force Needs Oar Point''' was a [[Second World War]] [[advanced landing ground]] located near [[Lymington]] in Hampshire, England.<ref name="Jefford169">Jefford 1988, p. 169</ref> Constructed in 1943 it was used from April 1944 as a base for [[Hawker Typhoon]] fighter-bomber squadrons of [[No. 146 Wing RAF|No. 146 Wing]] of the [[RAF Second Tactical Air Force|2nd Tactical Air Force]] supporting the Normandy landings. All four operational squadrons moved to [[RAF Hurn]] for two weeks before moving on to France by July 1944 and the airfield was returned to agricultural use in 1945.<ref nam"nop">[http://daveg4otu.tripod.com/airfields/nop.html Needs Oar Point]</ref><ref>[http://www.lymington.org/newforest/53.html Needs Oar Point Airfield]</ref>
==Units and aircraft== *[[No. 193 Squadron RAF]] with [[Hawker Typhoon|Hawker Typhoon IB]]s from 11 April to 3 July 1944.<ref name="Jefford67">Jefford 1988, p. 67</ref> *[[No. 197 Squadron RAF]] with Hawker Typhoon IBs from 10 April 1944 to 3 July 1944.<ref name="Jefford67" /> *[[No. 257 Squadron RAF]] with Hawker Typhoon IBs from 10 April 1944 to 2 July 1944<ref name="Jefford79">Jefford 1988, p. 79</ref> *[[No. 266 Squadron RAF]] with Hawker Typhoon IBs from 10 April 1944 to 29 June 1944; it temporarily moved to [[RAF Snaith]] in Yorkshire between 27 April 1944 and 6 May 1944.<ref name="Jefford81">Jefford 1988, p. 81</ref> *No. 413 (Polish) Repair and Salvage Unit was based on the airfield between 19 June 1944 and 21 July 1944.<ref>Sturtivant 2007, p.223</ref>
